Anonymous Sat 29 Dec 2018 13:51:22 No.20315801 Report
Quoted By: >>20319822
>>20312422
I dig and like to write in all three subgenres (high fantasy, pure sci-fi, blended), but never forget picrelated. Sci-fi is fantasy that partly draws its allure from both the imagination and the reader's perception of a setting's potential. Readers want things to be explained and laid out for them without ruining the story; if an author handwaves common questions away, he or she risks erring on suspension of disbelief and losing his or her reader's interest. When you remove the possibility of magic from a fantasy setting wherein impossible phenomena and actions are commonplace, a reader is left with only two reasonable umbrella explanations: nature and technology. You can do absolutely anything with the latter, the trick is retaining that awe of the future while pushing the boundaries of what can be believed to be achievable given time. Cyberpunk settings are more and more in vogue because many people feel like they're on the cusp of technological advents that make those settings feasible.

I get the feeling that we're arguing two parallel but different points.
Magic, as a concept in the context of reality, where there is no such thing, is a easy shorthand for someone to explain something they don't understand because they don't have the prerequisite knowledge to understand why it works. That thing still doesn't break the hard laws of the universe though.
Magic in a (high fantasy or the like) fictional context, where it does exist, is not the same as science. Because to say so would be at odds with what science fundamentally is, which is to understand and work within universal limits. It's impossible to teleport, or contain energy in dense enough amounts to do half of the things your average wizard may be able to do without severely affecting their surounding environment, impossible to move faster than the speed of light, impossible to make dense objects fly without some, probably significant, active force counteracting the effects of gravity on that object, impossible to contain mass in a truly smaller space (as in it's really the same object and not some energy converted facsimile or the like), etc.
And most importantly, regardless of whatever the principle or thing is in question that may seem impossible, there is always an explanation that is consistent with the rest of the universe as to /why/ that works. Something you actively don't get in any magic system. Things just happen with magic because they're straight willed to happen.
